      <Fragment slot="smlTitle">
        Shelf Impact and Print-Ready Files
      </Fragment>
      <Fragment slot="content">
        Packaging design is where graphic design meets engineering, and most designers underestimate the engineering part. You're not designing a flat rectangle in Illustrator — you're designing a three-dimensional object that needs to survive manufacturing, shipping, stacking, shelf placement, and the three seconds a customer spends deciding between your product and the one next to it.

        That three-second window is everything. It's called shelf impact, and it's the single most important metric in packaging design. Your packaging doesn't need to be beautiful — it needs to be noticeable. There's a difference. Beautiful packaging that blends in with every other product on the shelf is a failure. Bold, clear, slightly aggressive packaging that catches the eye from two metres away is doing its job.

        Colour is your most powerful tool for shelf impact. Look at the competitive shelf — the actual shelf, not a mockup — and identify the dominant colour palette. Then go somewhere else. If every competitor in the category uses blue, go orange. If everyone's doing matte earth tones, go glossy and vivid. The goal is contrast against the competitive set, not harmony. You want your product to visually interrupt the shelf.

        Typography hierarchy on packaging needs to be ruthless. You have three levels that matter: brand name, product name, and the single most compelling benefit or descriptor. Everything else is secondary. Ingredients lists, certifications, regulatory text — they need to be there, but they don't need to compete with your primary messaging. I see packaging designs where the brand name, product name, flavour variant, tagline, and three certifications are all fighting for attention at the same size. The result is that none of them win.

        Materials matter more than most designers realise, because material choice affects everything: print quality, perceived value, environmental impact, and cost. Uncoated kraft stock says "natural and sustainable." Soft-touch matte lamination says "premium." High-gloss says "bold and consumer-facing." Rigid boxes say "luxury." Each material creates a tactile expectation that either aligns with your brand positioning or undermines it.

        Sustainability in packaging is no longer a nice-to-have — it's a purchasing decision factor, especially in Australia. Recyclable materials, minimal plastic, soy-based inks, and compostable options are all commercially viable now. But here's the trap: don't greenwash. If your packaging is 90% plastic with a tiny "recyclable" symbol in the corner, consumers will notice. If you're genuinely using sustainable materials, make it a visible part of the design story.

        The unboxing experience is packaging's second act. It used to be that packaging just needed to protect the product and look good on a shelf. Now it needs to perform on camera too. Instagram and TikTok have turned unboxing into a marketing channel. Tissue paper, custom tape, printed interiors, thank-you cards — these details turn a transaction into content that your customers create for free. The ROI on a $0.50 tissue paper insert that generates a social post reaching 10,000 people is absurd.

        Let's talk about the technical side, because this is where designers who only work in digital tend to struggle. Print-ready packaging files are not the same as web assets. You're working in CMYK, not RGB. You need bleed — typically 3mm on all sides. You need to account for safe zones where critical text and imagery must stay clear of fold lines and cut lines. You need to work from the printer's dieline template, not a rectangle you drew yourself.

        Spot colours and special finishes — foil stamping, embossing, spot UV — can elevate packaging dramatically, but they add cost and complexity. A spot UV varnish on a logo creates a tactile, premium feel, but it requires a separate plate and increases your per-unit cost. Know the budget before you design the finish. There's nothing worse than presenting a concept with three special finishes to a client who needs to print 50,000 units at $0.30 each.

        Proofing is critical. Always request a physical proof from the printer before approving a full run. Screen colours lie. What looks like a rich navy on your calibrated monitor might print as a muddy dark blue on the actual stock. A physical proof catches colour issues, registration problems, and finishing quality before you've committed to 10,000 units you can't sell.

        One last thing: design for the production run, not the prototype. What works as a hand-assembled mockup might be impossible at scale. Talk to your printer early. Talk to them often. The best packaging designers treat their printer as a collaborator, not a vendor. Those conversations save money, avoid surprises, and usually lead to better design solutions than you'd find working in isolation.

        Good packaging design sells the product before the customer ever reads a word. That's the standard.
